XX INTRODUCTION.

‘⁶ Seeing that the calculation of this table, which ought to have been perfected by the labour and pains of many calcula? tom, has been accomplished by that of one alone, it will not be surprising if many errors have crept into it. I beseech you, benevolent readers, pardon these, whether occasioned by the weariness of calculation, or an oversight of the press 3 for as for myself, the infirm state of my health, and weightier occupatione, have prevented my adding the last finish. But if I shall understand that the use of this invention proves

· acceptable to the learned, I may, perhaps, in a short time

(God willing) publish the philosophy of it, and the method either of amending this Canon, or of constructing a new one upon a more convenient plan3 that thus, through the dili- gence of many calculators, a Canon, more highly finished and accurate than the labour of a single individua] could accom- plish, may at length see the light. Nothing is perfect at its birth.’'
